			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Just make sure your Linksys has the most recent patches and updates for the firmware. Also they have a step by step guide to securing it on their website somewhere, I'd suggest going through that.
<br />

<br />
You should have WEP Keys on, and the Linksys wireless should be instructed to only allow connections from the MAC addresses of your wireless devices, so that nobody else can hop on just by bringing a device in range.
<br />

<br />
There's a Linux firmware replacement for those linksys now that kicks ten kinds of %@$#. Apparently it's got a killer GUI and every kind of firewall ability in the book, including VPN, and it's far more secure than the original linksys product. You'll void your warranty by using it tho, so I'd stay away from it for now, at least until the thing is old and linksys has stopped providing support for it.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
